        <h2>Types of Travel Insurance Coverage</h2>
        <p>Medical coverage represents the most critical component of travel insurance, covering emergency medical treatment, hospital stays, and prescription medications abroad. This coverage becomes especially important in countries with expensive healthcare systems or limited medical facilities.</p>

        <p>Emergency evacuation coverage pays for transportation to appropriate medical facilities or repatriation to your home country when local medical care is inadequate. These costs can easily reach hundreds of thousands of dollars, making evacuation coverage essential for remote or developing destinations.</p>

        <p>Trip cancellation and interruption coverage reimburses non-refundable trip costs when you must cancel or cut short your trip due to covered reasons like illness, family emergencies, or natural disasters. This protection becomes more valuable for expensive trips or those booked far in advance.</p>

        <h2>What Travel Insurance Typically Covers</h2>
        <p>Most comprehensive travel insurance policies cover emergency medical treatment, including doctor visits, hospital stays, emergency dental care, and prescription medications. Coverage limits vary by policy, with higher-end plans offering more generous medical benefits.</p>

        <p>Baggage protection covers lost, stolen, or damaged luggage and personal belongings, though coverage limits are often modest and may not fully replace expensive items. Some policies also provide coverage for baggage delays, reimbursing essential items when luggage is delayed for specified periods.</p>

        <p>Travel delay coverage reimburses additional expenses like meals and accommodation when flights are delayed or cancelled for covered reasons. This protection helps manage unexpected costs during travel disruptions beyond your control.</p>

        <h2>Common Exclusions and Limitations</h2>
        <p>Pre-existing medical conditions are often excluded unless you purchase coverage within a specified time frame after making your initial trip deposit and meet other requirements. Understanding these exclusions is crucial for travelers with ongoing health issues.</p>

        <p>High-risk activities like extreme sports, mountaineering, or adventure activities may be excluded from standard policies. Travelers planning these activities should seek specialized coverage or policy riders that include adventure sports protection.</p>

        <p>Alcohol or drug-related incidents, illegal activities, and travel to countries under government travel warnings are typically excluded from coverage. Reading policy exclusions carefully helps avoid surprises when filing claims.</p>

